The PFAssistive Framework is an Objective-C framework wrapping Apple's accessibility API. It is intended for use with Cocoa client applications. Version 3.1.2 of the framework is a Universal binary for client applications running natively under Mac OS X 10.5 Leopard and newer on Power PC and Intel Macintosh computers. It supports both 32-bit and (on Intel) 64-bit client applications with reference counted memory management. Support for garbage-collected client applications is not available.\
\
The framework is designed to enable Cocoa developers to take full advantage of the accessibility API to write assistive and other client applications using familiar Cocoa techniques, without having to learn the intricacies of writing directly to the accessibility C API. It incorporates workarounds for all bugs known to us in Apple's implementation of the accessibility API. Among other useful features of the framework, it declares an Objective-C delegate method that makes it particularly easy for client applications to monitor accessibility notifications from any application running on the computer.\
\
Older versions of the framework are available for older versions of Mac OS X. Use PFAssistive Framework version 2.0 for applications running natively under Mac OS X 10.4 Tiger on Power PC and Intel Macintosh computers. Use PFAssistive Framework version 1.4.1 for applications running under Mac OS X 10.2 Jaguar and 10.3 Panther on Power PC computers, and under Mac OS X 10.3.9 Panther on Intel computers using Rosetta.\
\
You may publish and distribute the framework with your products subject to the distribution license terms summarized below.\
\
The framework is documented in English in the English.lproj subfolder of the Resources folder in the framework bundle. The documentation, along with sample code in the form of a simple screen reader, is also available for download on the website.\
\
For an example of an assistive application that uses the PFAssistive Framework as its accessibility engine, download a free 30-day trial version of UI Browser at pfiddlesoft.com/uibrowser/. UI Browser is, among other things, a developer's tool to test the correctness and functionality of an application's implementation of the accessibility API.\
