\i\b \cf0 About the Accessibility API
\i0\b0 \
\
Apple introduced the accessibility API in Mac OS X 10.2.0 Jaguar. Apple introduced many enhancements and bug fixes in Mac OS X 10.3 Panther and 10.4 Tiger and increased functionality in Mac OS X 10.5 Leopard and Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard.\
\
The accessibility API gives assistive applications the ability to read and manipulate the graphical user interface (GUI) of all applications that use the standard Cocoa or Carbon frameworks for their user interface elements (UI elements), as well as those that implement accessibility in custom UI element code. It also gives assistive applications the ability to detect accessibility notifications from any application.\
\
Apple introduced the accessibility API so that Macintosh applications can be written to comply with Section 508 of the federal Workforce Investment Act of 1998 and its requirements regarding access to electronic and information technology for persons with disabilities. Assistive applications allow the use of special software and hardware for computer input and output, such as screen readers and alternatives to the mouse and keyboard, to enable persons with disabilities to take full advantage of accessible applications. In addition, the API can be used to write any application that needs to query, respond to or control the user interface of another application. UI Browser is an example of such an application.\
